{{Infobox prepared food | name = Diples | image = 2011 Greek Diples.JPG | image_size = 300px | imagesize = | caption = | alternate_name = Thiples | country = [[Greece]] | region = | creator = | course = [[Dessert]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Dough]], syrup or honey | variations = | calories = | other = }} '''Diples''' or '''Thiples''' ({{lang-el|Δίπλες}}) is a [[Greek cuisine|Greek]] [[dessert]] from the Peloponnese, made of thin sheet-like dough. They are essentially the same as [[angel wings]], except that they are dipped in syrup rather than served dry.
The dough is rolled into long, thin strips, fried and folded in hot oil and then dipped in a sugar or honey syrup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thursdayfordinner.com/2008/12/diples-thiples-honey-rolls-greek-dessert |title=Diples (Thiples) (Honey Rolls) Greek Dessert |publisher=Thursday for Dinner |accessdate=2009-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.univers-recette.com/recette-699-n%C5%93uds-thiples.html |title = Recette Nœuds (Thiples) - Cuisine du monde |publisher = Univers recette |language = French |accessdate = 2009-11-08 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090429040016/http://www.univers-recette.com/recette-699-n%C5%93uds-thiples.html |archivedate = 2009-04-29 |df = }}</ref> Diples can be made in different shapes, of which the most common are bow ties and spirals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://greekfood.about.com/od/dessertspastriessweets/r/thiplesouzo.htm |title=Thiples: Fried Honey Pastries |author=Nancy Gaifyllia |publisher=About.com |accessdate=2009-11-08}}</ref> Diples are a typical dessert in the [[Peloponnese]] and are also served at weddings and at New Year's celebrations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fathertimes.net/greeknewyear.htm |title=New Year Traditions: Greek New Year |publisher=Australian Media Pty Ltd |accessdate=2009-11-08}}</ref>
Another form uses an iron [[mold (manufacturing)|mould]] dipped in diples [[Batter (cooking)|batter]] and cooked in [[cooking oil]] until the diples separates from the mould. It is topped with syrup, crushed [[walnut]]s, and [[cinnamon]].
<gallery> File:Diples.jpg|Diples File:Greek diples.jpg|Diples made on an iron [[mold (manufacturing)|mould]] dipped in [[Batter (cooking)|batter]] and cooked in [[cooking oil]] </gallery>
