heiup.uni-heidelberg.de/journals/index.php/transcultural/article/view/12313/8711#_edn32 endnote #32]. (Accessed 3 September 2016.)</ref> an [[Eastern Iranian people]] who inhabited Turpan as an ethnic minority community during the phases of [[Tang dynasty|Tang Chinese]] (7th–8th century) and [[Kingdom of Qocho|Uyghur rule]] (9th–13th century).<ref>Hansen, Valerie (2012), ''The Silk Road: A New History'', Oxford University Press, p. 98, {{ISBN|978-0-19-993921-3}}.</ref>| footer_align = left | image1 = UrumqiWarrior.jpg | width1 = 110 | caption1  = | image2 = Central Asian Buddhist Monks.jpeg | width2 = 195| caption2  = }}

===Hellenistic Greeks===
{{further information|China-Greece relations|History of Xinjiang#Early Caucasian inhabitants}}
Before the 13th century AD, instances of Europeans going to China or of Chinese going to Europe were very rare.<ref name="Roux, p.465"/> [[Euthydemus I]], [[Hellenistic period|Hellenistic]] ruler of the [[Greco-Bactrian Kingdom]] in [[Central Asia]] during the 3rd century BC, led an expedition into the [[Tarim Basin]] (modern [[Xinjiang]], China) in search of precious metals.<ref name="tarn 1966 pp109-111">W.W. Tarn (1966), ''The Greeks in Bactria and India'', reprint edition, London & New York: Cambridge University Press, pp 109–111.</ref><ref>For [[Strabo]]'s depiction of this event, see Christopoulos, Lucas (August 2012), "Hellenes and Romans in Ancient China (240 BC – 1398 AD)," in Victor H. Mair (ed), ''Sino-Platonic Papers'', No. 230, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, University of Pennsylvania Department of East Asian Languages and Civilizations, p. 8, ISSN 2157-9687.</ref> Greek influence as far east as the Tarim Basin at this time also seems to be confirmed by the discovery of the [[Sampul tapestry]], a woolen wall hanging with the painting of a blue-eyed soldier, possibly a Greek, and a prancing [[centaur]], a common Hellenistic [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] from [[Greek mythology]].<ref name="christoupoulos 2012 pp15-16">Christopoulos, Lucas (August 2012), "Hellenes and Romans in Ancient China (240 BC – 1398 AD)," in Victor H. Mair (ed), ''Sino-Platonic Papers'', No. 230, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, University of Pennsylvania Department of East Asian Languages and Civilizations, pp 15–16, ISSN 2157-9687.</ref><ref>Valerie Hansen (2012). The Silk Road: A New History. Oxford & New York: Oxford University Press, p. 202, pl. 13 text, {{ISBN|978-0-19-515931-8}}.</ref><ref>Zhao Feng (2004). "Wall hanging with centaur and warrior," in James C.Y. Watt, John P. O'Neill et. al. (eds) and trans. Ching-Jung Chen et. al., ''China: Dawn of a Golden Age, 200–750 A.D.'', New Haven & London: Yale University Press, Metropolitan Museum of Art, pp 194–195. {{ISBN|978-1-58839-126-1}}.</ref> However, it is known that other [[Indo-European migrations|Indo-European peoples]] such as the [[Yuezhi]], [[Saka]],<ref>Yu Taishan (June 2010), "The Earliest Tocharians in China" in Victor H. Mair (ed), ''Sino-Platonic Papers, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences'', University of Pennsylvania Department of East Asian Languages and Civilizations, p. 13–14, 21–22.</ref><ref>Bailey, H.W. (1996) "Khotanese Saka Literature", in Ehsan Yarshater (ed), ''The Cambridge History of Iran, Vol III: The Seleucid, Parthian, and Sasanian Periods, Part 2'' (reprint edition), Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp 1230–1231.</ref><ref name="tremblay 2007 p77"/> and [[Tocharians]]<ref name="tremblay 2007 p77">Xavier Tremblay (2007), "The Spread of Buddhism in Serindia: Buddhism Among Iranians, Tocharians and Turks before the 13th Century," in Ann Heirman and Stephan Peter Bumbacker (eds), ''The Spread of Buddhism'', Leiden & Boston: Koninklijke Brill, p. 77, {{ISBN|978-90-04-15830-6}}.</ref><ref>Mallory, J.P.; Mair, Victor H. (2000), ''The Tarim Mummies: Ancient China and the Mystery of the Earliest Peoples from the West'', London: Thames & Hudson, pp 270–297 {{ISBN|978-0-500-05101-6}}.</ref> inhabited [[Western Regions|the Tarim Basin]] before and after it was brought under [[Han Chinese]] influence during the reign of [[Emperor Wu of Han]] (r. 141–87 BC).<ref>Torday, Laszlo. (1997). ''Mounted Archers: The Beginnings of Central Asian History''. Durham: The Durham Academic Press, pp 80–81, {{ISBN|978-1-900838-03-0}}.</ref><ref>Yü, Ying-shih. (1986). "Han Foreign Relations," in ''The Cambridge History of China: Volume I: the Ch'in and Han Empires, 221 B.C. – A.D. 220'', 377–462. Edited by Denis Twitchett and Michael Loewe. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp 377–388, 391, {{ISBN|978-0-521-24327-8}}.</ref><ref>Chang, Chun-shu. (2007). The Rise of the Chinese Empire: Volume II; Frontier, Immigration, & Empire in Han China, 130 B.C. – A.D. 157. Ann Arbor: University of Michigan Press, pp 5–8 {{ISBN|978-0-472-11534-1}}.</ref><ref>Di Cosmo, Nicola. (2002). ''Ancient China and Its Enemies: The Rise of Nomadic Power in East Asian History''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp. 174–189, 196–198, 241–242 {{ISBN|978-0-521-77064-4}}.</ref>

At the cemetery in Sampul (Chinese: 山普拉), ~14&nbsp;km from the archaeological site of [[Khotan]] in [[Lop County]], Xinjiang, China,<ref name="chengzhi 2007"/> where the aforementioned Sampul tapestry was found,<ref name="christoupoulos 2012 pp15-16"/> the local inhabitants buried their dead there from roughly 217 BC to 283 AD.<ref>Christopoulos, Lucas (August 2012), "Hellenes and Romans in Ancient China (240 BC – 1398 AD)," in Victor H. Mair (ed), ''Sino-Platonic Papers'', No. 230, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, University of Pennsylvania Department of East Asian Languages and Civilizations, p. 27, ISSN 2157-9687.</ref> [[Mitochondrial DNA]] analysis of the human remains has revealed genetic affinities to peoples from the [[Caucasus]], specifically a [[maternal]] lineage linked to [[Ossetians]] and [[Iranian peoples|Iranians]], as well as an Eastern-Mediterranean [[paternal]] lineage.<ref name="chengzhi 2007">Chengzhi Xie et al., "[http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/10002007088537493 Mitochondrial DNA analysis of ancient Sampula population in Xinjiang]," in ''Progress in Natural Science'', vol. 17, (August 2007), pp 927–33.</ref><ref name="christopoulos 2012 footnote46">Christopoulos, Lucas (August 2012), "Hellenes and Romans in Ancient China (240 BC – 1398 AD)," in Victor H. Mair (ed), ''Sino-Platonic Papers'', No. 230, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, University of Pennsylvania Department of East Asian Languages and Civilizations, p. 27 & footnote #46, ISSN 2157-9687.</ref> Seeming to confirm this link, from historical accounts it is known that [[Alexander the Great]], who married a [[Sogdia]]n woman from [[Bactria]] named [[Roxana]],<ref name="livius roxane">Livius.org. "[http://www.livius.org/articles/person/roxane/ Roxane]." ''Articles on Ancient History''. Page last modified 17 August 2015. Retrieved on 8 September 2016.</ref><ref name="strachan 2008 p87">Strachan, Edward and Roy Bolton (2008), ''Russia and Europe in the Nineteenth Century'', London: Sphinx Fine Art, p. 87, {{ISBN|978-1-907200-02-1}}.</ref><ref>For another publication calling her "Sogdian", see Christopoulos, Lucas (August 2012), "Hellenes and Romans in Ancient China (240 BC – 1398 AD)," in Victor H. Mair (ed), ''Sino-Platonic Papers'', No. 230, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, University of Pennsylvania Department of East Asian Languages and Civilizations, p. 4, ISSN 2157-9687.</ref> encouraged his [[Ancient Macedonian army|soldiers and generals]] to marry local women; consequentially the later kings of the [[Seleucid Empire]] and Greco-Bactrian Kingdom had a mixed [[Persian people|Persian]]-[[Greek people|Greek]] ethnic background.<ref>Holt, Frank L. (1989), ''Alexander the Great and Bactria: the Formation of a Greek Frontier in Central Asia'', Leiden, New York, Copenhagen, Cologne: E. J. Brill, pp 67–8, {{ISBN|90-04-08612-9}}.</ref><ref>Ahmed, S. Z. (2004), ''Chaghatai: the Fabulous Cities and People of the Silk Road'', West Conshokoken: Infinity Publishing, p. 61.</ref><ref>Magill, Frank N. et al. (1998), ''The Ancient World: Dictionary of World Biography, Volume 1'', Pasadena, Chicago, London,: Fitzroy Dearborn Publishers, Salem Press, p. 1010, {{ISBN|0-89356-313-7}}.</ref><ref>Lucas Christopoulos writes the following: "''The kings (or soldiers) of the Sampul cemetery came from various origins, composing as they did a homogenous army made of Hellenized Persians, western Scythians, or Sacae Iranians from their mother's side, just as were most of  the  second  generation  of  Greeks  colonists  living  in  the  Seleucid  Empire.  Most  of  the  soldiers  of  Alexander  the Great who stayed in Persia, India and central Asia had married local women, thus their leading generals were mostly Greeks from their father's side or had Greco-Macedonian grandfathers. Antiochos had a Persian mother, and all the later Indo-Greeks or Greco-Bactrians were revered in the population as locals, as they used both Greek and Bactrian scripts  on  their  coins  and  worshipped  the  local  gods.  The  DNA  testing  of  the  Sampul  cemetery  shows  that the occupants had paternal origins in the eastern part of the Mediterranean''"; see Christopoulos, Lucas (August 2012), "Hellenes and Romans in Ancient China (240 BC – 1398 AD)," in Victor H. Mair (ed), ''Sino-Platonic Papers'', No. 230, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, University of Pennsylvania Department of East Asian Languages and Civilizations, p. 27 & footnote #46, ISSN 2157-9687.</ref>

===Ancient Romans===
{{main article|Sino-Roman relations}}
Beginning in the age of [[Augustus]] (r. 27 BC – 14 AD), the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]], including authors such as [[Pliny the Elder]], mentioned contacts with the ''[[Seres]]'', whom they identified as the producers of [[History of silk|silk]] from distant [[East Asia]] and could have been the Chinese or even any number of middlemen of various ethnic backgrounds along the Silk Road of Central Asia and [[Northwest China]].<ref>W.W. Tarn (1966), ''The Greeks in Bactria and India'', reprint edition, London & New York: Cambridge University Press, pp 110–111.</ref> The [[Han dynasty|Eastern-Han era]] Chinese general [[Ban Chao]], [[Protector General of the Western Regions]], explored Central Asia and in 97 AD dispatched his envoys [[Gan Ying]] to [[Daqin]] (i.e. the [[Roman Empire]]).<ref>Yü, Ying-shih. (1986). "Han Foreign Relations," in The Cambridge History of China: Volume I: the Ch'in and Han Empires, 221 B.C. – A.D. 220, 377–462. Edited by Denis Twitchett and Michael Loewe. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp 460–461, {{ISBN|978-0-521-24327-8}}.</ref><ref>de Crespigny, Rafe. (2007). A Biographical Dictionary of Later Han to the Three Kingdoms (23–220 AD). Leiden: Koninklijke Brill, pp 239–240, {{ISBN|978-90-04-15605-0}}.</ref> Gan was dissuaded by [[Parthian Empire|Parthian authorities]] from venturing further than the [[Persian Gulf]], although he wrote a detailed report about the Roman Empire, [[Demography of the Roman Empire|its cities]], [[Cursus publicus|postal network]] and [[Roman consul|consular system of government]], and presented this to the Han court.<ref>Wood, Frances. (2002). The Silk Road: Two Thousand Years in the Heart of Asia. Berkeley and Los Angeles: University of California Press, pp 46–47, {{ISBN|978-0-520-24340-8}}.</ref><ref>Morton, William Scott and Charlton M. Lewis. (2005). China: Its History and Culture: Fourth Edition. New York City: McGraw-Hill, p. 59, {{ISBN|978-0-07-141279-7}}.</ref> Subsequently, there was a series of [[Sino-Roman relations|Roman embassies in China]] lasting from the 2nd to 3rd centuries AD, as recorded in Chinese sources. In 166 AD the ''[[Book of Later Han]]'' records that [[History of Rome|Romans]] reached China from [[Roman trade with India|the maritime south]] and presented gifts to the court of [[Emperor Huan of Han]] (r. 146–168 AD), claiming they represented Roman emperor [[Marcus Aurelius|Marcus Aurelius Antoninus]] (''Andun'' 安敦) (r. 161–180 AD).<ref name="de crespigny 2007 600">[[Rafe de Crespigny|de Crespigny, Rafe]]. (2007). ''A Biographical Dictionary of Later Han to the Three Kingdoms (23–220 AD)''. Leiden: Koninklijke Brill, p. 600, {{ISBN|978-90-04-15605-0}}.</ref><ref>[[Yu Ying-shih|Yü, Ying-shih]]. (1986). "Han Foreign Relations," in Denis Twitchett and Michael Loewe (eds), ''The Cambridge History of China: Volume I: the Ch'in and Han Empires, 221 B.C. – A.D. 220, 377–462'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp. 460–461, {{ISBN|978-0-521-24327-8}}.</ref> Historian [[Rafe de Crespigny]] speculates that they were [[Roman commerce|Roman merchants]] instead of official diplomats.<ref name="de crespigny 2007 600"/>

At the very least, archaeological evidence supports the claim in the ''[[Weilüe]]''<ref name="hill 2004 webpage">{{cite web|url=http://depts.washington.edu/uwch/silkroad/texts/weilue/weilue.html |title=The Peoples of the West from the Weilue'' 魏略 ''by Yu Huan'' 魚豢'': A Third Century Chinese Account Composed between 239 and 265, Quoted in zhuan 30 of the Sanguozhi, Published in 429 CE |first=Huan |last=Yu |editor= John E. Hill |translator= John E. Hill|website=Depts.washington.edu |date=September 2004 |accessdate=2016-09-17}}</ref> and ''[[Book of Liang]]''<ref name="halsall 2000"/> that Roman merchants were active in [[Southeast Asia]], if not the claim of their embassies arriving in China through [[Jiaozhi]], the Chinese-controlled province of northern [[Vietnam]].<ref name="young 2001 pp29-30"/> Roman golden [[medal]]lions from the reigns of [[Antoninus Pius]] and his adopted son Marcus Aurelius have been found in [[Oc Eo]] (near [[Ho Chi Minh City]]), a territory that belonged to the [[Kingdom of Funan]] bordering Jiaozhi.<ref name="young 2001 pp29-30">Gary K. Young (2001), Rome's Eastern Trade: International Commerce and Imperial Policy, 31 BC - AD 305, London & New York: Routledge, {{ISBN|0-415-24219-3}}, pp 29–30.</ref> Suggestive of even earlier activity is a [[Roman Republic|Republican]]-era [[Roman glass]] bowl unearthed from a [[Western Han]] tomb of [[Guangzhou]] (on the shores of the [[South China Sea]]) dated to the early 1st century BC,<ref>An, Jiayao. (2002), "When Glass Was Treasured in China," in Annette L. Juliano and Judith A. Lerner (eds), ''Silk Road Studies VII: Nomads, Traders, and Holy Men Along China's Silk Road'', 79–94, Turnhout: Brepols Publishers, {{ISBN|2-503-52178-9}}, p. 83.</ref> in addition to ancient [[History of the Mediterranean region|Mediterranean goods]] found in [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], and [[Malaysia]].<ref name="young 2001 pp29-30"/> The Greco-Roman geographer [[Ptolemy]] wrote in his [[Antonine]]-era ''[[Geography (Ptolemy)|Geography]]'' that beyond the [[Golden Chersonese]] ([[Malay Peninsula]]) was a port city called [[Kattigara]] discovered by a Greek sailor named Alexander, a site [[Ferdinand von Richthofen]] assumed was Chinese-controlled [[Hanoi]],<ref>[[Ferdinand von Richthofen]], ''China'', Berlin, 1877, Vol.I, pp. 504–510; cited in Richard Hennig, ''Terrae incognitae : eine Zusammenstellung und kritische Bewertung der wichtigsten vorcolumbischen Entdeckungsreisen an Hand der daruber vorliegenden Originalberichte, Band I, Altertum bis Ptolemäus'', Leiden, Brill, 1944, pp.387, 410–411; cited in Zürcher (2002), pp. 30–31.</ref> but given the archaeological evidence could have been Oc Eo.<ref name="young 2001 pp29-30"/><ref>For further information on the archaeological site at [[Oc Eo]] in Vietnam, see: Milton Osborne (2006), ''The Mekong: Turbulent Past, Uncertain Future'', Crows Nest: Allen & Unwin, revised edition, first published in 2000, {{ISBN|1-74114-893-6}}, pp 24–25.</ref> Roman coins have been found in China, but far fewer [[Indo-Roman trade relations|than in India]].<ref name="ball 2016 p154">Warwick Ball (2016), ''Rome in the East: Transformation of an Empire'', 2nd edition, London & New York: Routledge, {{ISBN|978-0-415-72078-6}}, p. 154.</ref>

It is possible that a group of Greek acrobatic performers, who claimed to be from a place "[[Daqin#Geographical descriptions in the Weilüe|west of the seas]]" (i.e. [[Roman Egypt]], which the ''Book of Later Han'' related to the "Daqin" empire), were presented by a king of [[Burma]] to [[Emperor An of Han]] in 120 AD.<ref>[[Ban Gu]] (班固), [[Houhanshu]] (後漢書) (Later Han dynasty annals), chap. 86, "Traditions of the Southern Savages; The South-Western Tribes" ([[Nanman]], Xinanyi zhuan 南蠻西南夷列傳). Liezhuan 76. (Beijing: Zhonghua Shuju 中華書局, 1962–1999), p. 1926. "永初元年," 徼外僬僥種夷陸類等三千餘口舉種内附，献象牙､水牛､封牛。 永寧元年，撣國王雍由調复遣使者詣闕朝賀，献樂及幻人，能變化吐火，自支解，易牛馬頭。又善跳丸， 數乃至千。自言我海西人。海西即大秦也，撣國西南通大秦。明年元會，安帝作變於庭，封雍由調爲漢大 都尉，赐印綬､金銀､彩繒各有差也."<br/>A translation of this passage into English, in addition to an explanation of how Greek athletic performers figured prominently in the neighboring [[Parthian Empire|Parthian]] and [[Kushan Empire]]s of Asia, is offered by Christopoulos, Lucas (August 2012), "Hellenes and Romans in Ancient China (240 BC – 1398 AD)," in Victor H. Mair (ed), ''Sino-Platonic Papers'', No. 230, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, University of Pennsylvania Department of East Asian Languages and Civilizations, pp 40–41, ISSN 2157-9687:
<br/>"''The  first  year  of Yongning (120  AD),  the  southwestern  barbarian  king  of  the kingdom  of  Chan  (Burma),  Yongyou,  proposed illusionists  (jugglers)  who  could  metamorphose themselves and spit out fire; they could dismember themselves and change  an  ox  head  into  a  horse  head.  They  were  very skilful  in  acrobatics  and  they could do a thousand other things. They said that they were from the "west of the seas" (Haixi–Egypt). The west of the seas is the Daqin (Rome). The Daqin is situated  to  the  south-west of  the  Chan  country.  During  the  following  year,  Andi  organized festivities in his country residence and the acrobats were transferred to the  Han capital  where  they  gave  a  performance  to  the  court,  and  created  a  great  sensation.  They  received  the  honours  of  the Emperor,  with  gold  and  silver,  and every one of them received a different gift.''"</ref> It is known that in both the [[Parthian Empire]] and [[Kushan Empire]] of Asia, ethnic Greeks continued to be employed as entertainers such as musicians and athletes who engaged in athletic competitions.<ref>Christopoulos, Lucas (August 2012), "Hellenes and Romans in Ancient China (240 BC – 1398 AD)," in Victor H. Mair (ed), ''Sino-Platonic Papers'', No. 230, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, University of Pennsylvania Department of East Asian Languages and Civilizations, pp 40–41, ISSN 2157-9687:</ref><ref>Franz Cumont (1933), ''The Excavations of Dura-Europos: Preliminary Reports of the Seventh and Eighth Seasons of Work, Crai'', New  Haven, pp. 264–68.</ref>

===Byzantine Empire===
{{further information|Byzantine diplomacy|Byzantine-Mongol alliance|Tang dynasty}}
[[File:Emperor Taizong gives an audience to the ambassador of Tibet.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Emperor Taizong of Tang]] (r. 626–649) giving an audience to [[Gar Tongtsen Yulsung]], ambassador of the [[Tibetan Empire]], in a painting by [[Yan Liben]] (600–673 AD)]]
[[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] Greek historian [[Procopius]] stated that two [[Nestorian Christianity|Nestorian Christian]] monks eventually uncovered how [[silk]] was made. From this revelation, monks were sent by the Byzantine Emperor [[Justinian]] (ruled 527–565) as spies on the [[Silk Road]] from [[Constantinople]] to China and back to [[Smuggling of silkworm eggs into the Byzantine Empire|steal the silkworm eggs]].<ref name="Durant2011">{{cite book|author=Will Durant|title=The Age of Faith: The Story of Civilization|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cusRoE1OJvEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjB_e2e__nOAhVLJR4KHbZvA3M4ChDoAQgsMAM#v=onepage&q&f=false|date= 1949|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-4761-7|page=118}}</ref> This resulted in silk production in the Mediterranean, particularly in [[Soufli#Silk museums of Soufli|Thrace]], in northern Greece,<ref name="livius.org">[http://www.livius.org/sh-si/silk_road/silk_road.html "Silk Road"], LIVIUS Articles of Ancient History. 28 October 2010. Retrieved on 14 November 2010.</ref> and giving the [[Byzantine silk|Byzantine Empire a monopoly on silk production]] in medieval Europe until the loss of [[Lucania (theme)|its territories in Southern Italy]]. The Byzantine historian [[Theophylact Simocatta]], writing during the reign of [[Heraclius]] (r. 610–641), relayed information about [[Geography of China|China's geography]], its capital city ''Khubdan'' ([[Old Turkic language|Old Turkic]]: ''Khumdan'', i.e. [[Chang'an]]), its current ruler ''Taisson'' whose name meant "[[Son of Heaven|Son of Heaven]]" (Chinese: 天子 [[Chinese emperor|''Tianzi'']], although this could be derived from the name of [[Emperor Taizong of Tang]]), and correctly pointed to its reunification by the [[Sui dynasty]] (581–618) as occurring during the reign of [[Maurice (emperor)|Maurice]], noting that China had previously been divided politically along the [[Yangzi River]] by [[Southern and Northern dynasties|two warring nations]].<ref>Yule (1915), pp 29–31; see also footnote #4 on p. 29; footnote #2 on p. 30; and footnote #3 on page 31.</ref> The Chinese ''[[Old Book of Tang]]'' and ''[[New Book of Tang]]'' mention [[:zh:s:新唐書/卷221下|several embassies made by ''Fu lin'']] (拂菻; i.e. [[Byzantium]]), which they equated with [[Daqin]] (i.e. the [[Roman Empire]]), beginning in 643 with an embassy sent by the king ''Boduoli'' (波多力, i.e. [[Constans II|Constans II Pogonatos]]) to [[Emperor Taizong of Tang|Emperor Taizong]] of [[Tang dynasty|Tang]], bearing gifts such as [[Cranberry glass|red glass]].<ref name="halsall 2000">{{cite web|orig-year=1885|date=2000|author=Hirth, Friedrich|editor=Jerome S. Arkenberg|url=http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/eastasia/romchin1.html |title=East Asian History Sourcebook: Chinese Accounts of Rome, Byzantium and the Middle East, c. 91 B.C.E. - 1643 C.E. |publisher=[[Fordham University]]|website=Fordham.edu|accessdate=2016-09-14}}</ref> These histories also provided cursory descriptions of [[Constantinople]], [[Walls of Constantinople|its walls]], and [[Siege of Constantinople (674-678)|how it was besieged]] by ''Da shi'' (大食; the Arabs of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]]) and their commander "Mo-yi" (摩拽; i.e. [[Muawiyah I]], governor of Syria before becoming [[caliph]]), who forced them to pay tribute.<ref name="halsall 2000"/> From [[Wenxian Tongkao|Chinese records]] it is known that [[Michael VII Doukas]] (Mie li sha ling kai sa 滅力沙靈改撒) of ''Fu lin'' dispatched a diplomatic mission to China's [[Song dynasty]] that arrived in 1081, during the reign of [[Emperor Shenzong of Song]].<ref name="halsall 2000"/><ref name="SezginEhrig-Eggert1996">{{cite book|author1=Fuat Sezgin|author2=Carl Ehrig-Eggert|author3=Amawi Mazen|author4=E. Neubauer|title=نصوص ودراسات من مصادر صينية حول البلدان الاسلامية|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k3ygAAAAMAAJ&q=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrraCw9fnOAhXBGR4KHaWMDgAQ6AEIODAF|year=1996|place=Frankfurt am Main|publisher=Institut für Geschichte der Arabisch-Islamischen Wissenschaften (Institute for the History of Arabic-Islamic Science at the Johann Wolfgang Goethe University)|page=25}}</ref> Some Chinese [[History of the Song dynasty|during the Song period]] showed interest in countries to the west, such as the early 13th-century [[Quanzhou]] customs inspector [[Zhao Rugua]], who described the ancient [[Lighthouse of Alexandria]] in his ''[[Zhu fan zhi]]''.<ref>Needham, Joseph (1971). ''Science and Civilization in China: Volume 4, Physics and Physical Technology, Part 3: Civil Engineering and Nautics''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; rpr. Taipei: Caves Books, Ltd, 1986, p. 662.</ref>

==Merchants==
{{double image|right|PolosLeavingConstantinople.JPG|225|Yuan pottery incense burner.JPG|177|'''Left image:''' [[Niccolò and Maffeo Polo]] leaving [[Constantinople]] for the East, in 1259, from a 15th-century illuminated manuscript version of ''[[The Travels of Marco Polo]]''
<br/>'''Right image:''' A ''[[sancai]]''-glazed [[Chinese ceramics|Chinese ceramic]] [[incense burner]], [[Yuan dynasty]]}}
{{further information|Niccolò and Maffeo Polo|Marco Polo|The Travels of Marco Polo}}
[[File:Yuan stone Nestorian inscription (rep).JPG|thumb|Chinese stone inscription of a [[Church of the East in China|Nestorian]] [[Nestorian Cross|Christian Cross]] from a monastery of [[Fangshan District]] in [[Beijing]] (then called Dadu, or [[Khanbaliq]]), [[Yuan dynasty]]]]

According to the 9th-century ''[[Book of Roads and Kingdoms (ibn Khordadbeh)|Book of Roads and Kingdoms]]'' by [[ibn Khordadbeh]],<ref name="HirschmanYates2014">{{cite book|author1=Elizabeth Caldwell Hirschman|author2=Donald N. Yates|title=The Early Jews and Muslims of England and Wales: A Genetic and Genealogical History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zq9iAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=There+they+embark+on+the+Euphrates+and+reach+Baghdad,+whence+they+sail+down+the+Tigris,+to+al-Obolla.+From+al-Obolla+they+sail+for+Oman,+Sindh,+Hind,+and+China.&source=bl&ots=xVcj9SOyAI&sig=8X-87uFfxz8MfzoYsPkNZ0RLZxE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj3iMz4gtbPAhULWz4KHTzFBzEQ6AEIJTAB#v=onepage&q=There%20they%20embark%20on%20the%20Euphrates%20and%20reach%20Baghdad%2C%20whence%20they%20sail%20down%20the%20Tigris%2C%20to%20al-Obolla.%20From%20al-Obolla%20they%20sail%20for%20Oman%2C%20Sindh%2C%20Hind%2C%20and%20China.&f=false|date=29 April 2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-7684-8|pages=51–}}</ref> China was a destination for [[Radhanite#Text of Ibn Khordadbeh.27s account|Radhanite Jews]] buying boys, female slaves and eunuchs from Europe. During the subsequent [[Song dynasty|Song period]] there was also a community of [[Kaifeng Jews]] in China.<ref>Gernet, Jacques (1962). H.M. Wright (trans), ''Daily Life in China on the Eve of the Mongol Invasion, 1250–1276''. Stanford: Stanford University Press. {{ISBN|0-8047-0720-0}}, p. 82.</ref> The Spaniard, [[Benjamin of Tudela]] (from [[Tudela, Navarre|Navarre]]) was a 12th-century Jewish traveler whose ''Travels of Benjamin'' recorded vivid descriptions of Europe, Asia, and Africa, preceding those of [[Marco Polo]] by a hundred years.

Polo, a 13th-century merchant from the [[Republic of Venice]], describes his travels to [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan-dynasty]] China and the court of Mongol ruler [[Kublai Khan]], along with the preceding journeys made by [[Niccolò and Maffeo Polo]], his father and uncle, respectively, in his ''[[Travels of Marco Polo]]''. Polo related this account to [[Rustichello da Pisa]] around 1298 while they shared a [[Republic of Genoa|Genoese]] prison cell following their [[Battle of Curzola|capture in battle]].<ref>Polo, Marco; Latham, Ronald (translator) (1958), ''The Travels of Marco Polo'', New York: Penguin Books, p. 16, {{ISBN|0-14-044057-7}}.</ref><ref>Hoffman, Donald L. (1991). "Rusticiano da Pisa". In Lacy, Norris J. (ed.), ''The New Arthurian Encyclopedia''. New York: Garland, p. 392. {{ISBN|0-8240-4377-4}}.</ref> In his return trip to [[Persia]] from China (setting out from the port at [[Quanzhou]] in 1291), Marco Polo said that he accompanied the Mongol princess [[Kököchin]] in her intended marriage to [[Arghun]], ruler of the Mongol [[Ilkhanate]], but she instead married his son [[Ghazan]] following the former's sudden death.<ref>Ye, Yiliang (2010), "Introductory Essay: Outline of the Political Relations between Iran and China," in Ralph Kauz (ed.), ''Aspects of the Maritime Silk Road: From the Persian Gulf to the East China Sea'', Weisbaden: Harrassowitz Verlag, pp 5–6, {{ISBN|978-3-447-06103-2}}.</ref> Although Marco Polo's presence is omitted entirely, his story is confirmed by the 14th-century Persian historian  [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani]] in his ''[[Jami' al-tawarikh]]''.<ref>Morgan, D.O., "Marco Polo in China-Or Not," in ''The Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society'', Volume 6, Issue #2, 221–225, July 1996, p. 224.</ref>

Marco Polo accurately described geographical features of China such as [[Grand Canal of China|the Grand Canal]].<ref>Stephen G. Haw (2006), ''Marco Polo's China: a Venetian in the Realm of Kublai Khan'', London & New York: Routledge, pp 1–2, {{ISBN|0-415-34850-1}}.</ref> His detailed and accurate descriptions of [[Salt in Chinese history#Early modern technology|salt production]] confirm that he had actually been in China.<ref>Some scholars have suggested that Polo's knowledge was so detailed that he must have been the imperial official in charge of the Yangzhou salt works, but this suggestion has not been accepted. Leonardo Olschki, ''Marco Polo's Asia: an Introduction to His "Description of the World" Called "Il Milione.".'' (Berkeley: University of California Press, 1960), p. 174.</ref> Marco described salt wells and hills where salt could be mined, probably in [[Yunnan]], and reported that in the mountains "these rascals&nbsp;... have none of the Great Khan's paper money, but use salt instead&nbsp;... They have salt which they boil and set in a mold&nbsp;..."<ref>Hans Ulrich Vogel. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Ydo_9TEmuVQC&dq=isbn:9789004231931&source=gbs_navlinks_s Marco Polo Was in China: New Evidence from Currencies, Salts and Revenues].'' (Leiden; Boston: Brill,  2013;  {{ISBN|978-90-04-23193-1}}), pp. 290, 301–310.</ref> Polo also remarked how the Chinese burned [[History of paper|paper]] [[effigy|effigies]] shaped as male and female servants, camels, horses, suits of clothing and armor while [[Cremation|cremating]] the dead during [[Funerary art|funerary rites]].<ref>{{harvnb|Tsien|1985|p=105}}</ref>

When visiting [[Zhenjiang]] in [[Jiangsu]], China, Marco Polo noted that [[Christian church]]es had been built there.<ref name="emmerick 2003 p 275"/> His claim is confirmed by a Chinese text of the 14th century explaining how a [[Sogdia]]n named Mar-Sargis from [[Samarkand]] founded six [[Nestorianism|Nestorian Christian churches]] there in addition to one in [[Hangzhou]] during the second half of the 13th century.<ref name="emmerick 2003 p 275">Emmerick, R. E. (2003) "Iranian Settlement East of the Pamirs", in Ehsan Yarshater, ''The Cambridge History of Iran, Vol III: The Seleucid, Parthian, and Sasanian Periods'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, p 275.</ref> Nestorian Christianity had existed in China earlier during the [[Tang dynasty]] (618–907 AD) when a [[Persia]]n monk named [[Alopen]] (Chinese: ''Āluósī''; 阿羅本; 阿羅斯) came to the capital Chang'an in 653 to [[Proselytism|proselytize]], as described in a dual [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and [[Syriac language]] inscription from [[Chang'an]] (modern [[Xi'an]]) dated to the year 781.<ref>Emmerick, R. E. (2003) "Iranian Settlement East of the Pamirs", in Ehsan Yarshater, ''The Cambridge History of Iran, Vol III: The Seleucid, Parthian, and Sasanian Periods'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp 274–5.</ref>

Others were soon to follow. In about 1340 [[Francesco Balducci Pegolotti]], a merchant from [[Florence]], compiled a [[Pratica della mercatura|guide about trade in China]], a country he called ''[[Cathay]]'',<ref>"[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Francesco-Balducci-Pegolotti Francesco Balducci Pegolotti]." ''Encyclopædia Britannica'' (online source). Accessed 6 September 2016.</ref> noting the size of [[Khanbaliq]] (modern [[Beijing]]) and how merchants could exchange silver for [[Economy of the Song dynasty|Chinese]] [[Jiaozi (currency)|paper money]] that could be used to buy luxury items such as silk.<ref>Spielvogel, Jackson J. (2011). ''Western Civilization: a Brief History'', Boston: Wadsworth, Cencage Learning, p. 183, {{ISBN|0-495-57147-4}}.</ref> [[John Mandeville]], a mid-14th-century author and alleged Englishman from [[St Albans]], claimed to have lived in China and even served at the Mongol khan's court.<ref>Mandeville, John. (1983). C.W.R.D. Moseley (trans), ''The Travels of Sir John Mandeville''. London: Penguin Books Ltd., pp 9-11.</ref> However, certain parts of his accounts are considered dubious by modern scholars, with some conjecturing that he simply concocted his stories by using written accounts of China penned by other authors such as [[Odoric of Pordenone]].<ref>Mandeville, John. (1983). C.W.R.D. Moseley (trans), ''The Travels of Sir John Mandeville''. London: Penguin Books Ltd., pp 11-13.</ref> Marco Polo mentioned the heavy presence of [[Genoa|Genoese Italians]] at [[Tabriz]] (modern [[Iran]]) a city that Marco returned to from China via the [[Strait of Hormuz]] in 1293–1294.<ref>Virgil Ciocîltan (2012), ''The Mongols and the Black Sea Trade in the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Centuries'', Leiden: Brill, pp 119–121, {{ISBN|978-90-04-22666-1}}.</ref> The Italian [[Franciscan order|Franciscan]] monk [[John of Montecorvino]] took this same journey in reverse starting in 1291, setting out from Tabriz to [[Ormus]], sailing from there to China while accompanied by the Italian merchant Pietro de Lucalongo.<ref>Virgil Ciocîltan (2012), ''The Mongols and the Black Sea Trade in the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Centuries'', Leiden: Brill, p. 120, {{ISBN|978-90-04-22666-1}}.</ref> While Montecorvino became a bishop in Khanbaliq (Beijing), his friend Lucalongo continued to serve as a merchant there and even donated a large amount of money to maintain the local [[Church (building)|Catholic Church]].<ref>See footnote #268 in Virgil Ciocîltan (2012), ''The Mongols and the Black Sea Trade in the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Centuries'', Leiden: Brill, p. 120, {{ISBN|978-90-04-22666-1}}.</ref>

[[File:LetterInnocenceToTartarKingAndPeople a.jpg|thumb|160px|Text of the letter of [[Pope Innocent IV]] "to the ruler and people of the Tartars", brought to [[Güyüg Khan]] by [[John de Carpini]], 1245]]
[[File:Guyuk khan's Stamp 1246.jpg|thumb|160px|Seal of [[Güyük Khan]] using the classical [[Mongolian script]], as found in a letter sent to the Roman [[Pope Innocent IV]] in 1246.]]
[[File:LetterArghunToNicholasIV1290VaticanArchives.jpg|thumb|160px|Letter from [[Arghun]], Khan of the Mongol [[Ilkhanate]], to [[Pope Nicholas IV]], 1290.]]
[[File:GhazanSeal1302LetterToBonifaceVIII.JPG|thumb|160px|Seal of the Mongol ruler [[Ghazan]] in a 1302 letter to [[Pope Boniface VIII]], with an inscription in Chinese [[seal script]]]]
In [[Quanzhou|Zaytun]], the first harbour of China, there was a small Genoese colony, mentioned in 1326 by André de Pérouse. The most famous Italian resident of the city was [[:it:Andalò da Savignone|Andolo de Savignone]], who was sent to the West by the Khan in 1336 to obtain "100 horses and other treasures."<ref name="Roux, p.467"/> Following Savignone's visit, [[Giovanni de Marignolli|an ambassador]] was dispatched to China with one superb horse, which was later the object of [[Chinese poetry|Chinese poems]] and [[Chinese painting|paintings]].<ref name="Roux, p.467">Roux (1993), p. 467.</ref>

Other Venetians lived in China, including one who brought a letter to the West from John of Montecorvino in 1305. In 1339 a Venetian named Giovanni Loredano is recorded to have returned to Venice from China. A tombstone was also discovered in Yangzhou, in the name of [[Katarina Vilioni|Catherine de Villioni]], daughter of Dominici, who died there in 1342.<ref name="Roux, p.467"/>

The ''[[History of Yuan]]'' (chapter 134) records that a certain Ai-sie (transliteration of either Joshua or Joseph) from the country of Fu lin (i.e. the [[Byzantine Empire]]), initially in the service of [[Güyük Khan]], was well-versed in Western languages and had expertise in the fields of [[Byzantine medicine|medicine]] and [[Byzantine astronomy|astronomy]] that convinced Kublai Khan to offer him a position as the director of medical and astronomical boards. Kublai Khan eventually honored him with the title of Prince of Fu lin (Chinese: 拂菻王; ''Fú lǐn wáng''). His biography in the ''History of Yuan'' lists his children by their [[Chinese name]]s, which are similar to the [[Christian name]]s Elias (''Ye-li-ah''), Luke (''Lu-ko''), and Antony (''An-tun''), with a daughter named ''A-na-si-sz''.<ref name="bretschneider 1888p144">[[Emil Bretschneider|Bretschneider, Emil]] (1888), ''Medieval Researches from Eastern Asiatic Sources: Fragments Towards the Knowledge of the Geography and History of Central and Western Asia from the 13th to the 17th Century, Vol. 1'', Abingdon: Routledge, reprinted 2000, p. 144.</ref>

==Missionaries and diplomats==
{{Main article|Religion in the Mongol Empire|Roman Catholicism in China|Jesuit China missions|Protestant missions in China 1807–1953}}
{{further information|Christianity among the Mongols|Tibetan Buddhism|Chinese Buddhism|Buddhism in Mongolia|Tengriism|Islam during the Yuan dynasty|Islam in Mongolia}}
The Italian explorer and archbishop [[Giovanni da Pian del Carpine]] and Polish friar and traveler [[Benedykt Polak]] were the first papal envoys to reach [[Karakorum]] after being sent there by [[Pope Innocent IV]] in 1245.<ref name="fontana 2011 p116">Fontana, Michela (2011), ''Matteo Ricci: a Jesuit in the Ming Court'', Lanham: Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, p. 116, {{ISBN|978-1-4422-0586-4}}.</ref><ref name="Buell2010">{{cite book|author=Paul D. Buell|title=The A to Z of the Mongol World Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=se_OWGwQ_dcC&dq=nicholas%20in%20the%20year%201338%20had%20not%20yet%20arrive%20in%20peking%20for%20the%20christians%20there%20compalined%20ina%20letter%20written%20at%20the%20above%20that%20that%20they%20were%20eight%20years%20without%20a%20curate&source=gbs_book_other_versions|date=12 February 2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-1-4617-2036-2|pages=120–121}}</ref> The "''[[Ystoria Mongalorum|Historia Mongalorum]]''" was later written by Pian del Carpini, documenting his travels and a cursory history of the Mongols.<ref name="FriedmanFigg2013">{{cite book|author1=John Block Friedman|author2=Kristen Mossler Figg|title=Trade, Travel, and Exploration in the Middle Ages: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-OmCfNI_SxAC&pg=PA307&lpg=PA307&dq=China%27Franciscans+were+mentioned+in+his&source=bl&ots=lbP0lEzi7u&sig=lbuBQP-q95dAVd7tnIT1Nfw88T0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6pcjZhfrOAhWJKh4KHbOtDE4Q6AEIUDAH#v=onepage&q=China%27Franciscans%20were%20mentioned%20in%20his&f=false|date=4 July 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-59094-9|pages=307–}}</ref><ref name="Buell2003">{{cite book|author=Paul D. Buell|title=Historical Dictionary of the Mongol World Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y38YAwAAQBAJ&dq=nicholas%20in%20the%20year%201338%20had%20not%20yet%20arrive%20in%20peking%20for%20the%20christians%20there%20compalined%20ina%20letter%20written%20at%20the%20above%20that%20that%20they%20were%20eight%20years%20without%20a%20curate&source=gbs_book_other_versions|date=19 March 2003|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6602-7|pages=120–121}}</ref> Catholic missionaries soon established a considerable presence in China, due to the religious tolerance of the Mongols, due in no small part to the Khan's own great tolerance and open encouragement of the development of trade and intellectual [[avocation]]. The 18th-century English historian [[Edward Gibbon]] commented on the Mongols' religious tolerance and went as far as to compare the "religious laws" of [[Genghis Khan]] to equivalent ideas propounded by the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] English philosopher [[John Locke]].<ref>Morgan, David (2007), ''The Mongols'', Malden, MA: Blackwell Pub, p. 39, {{ISBN|978-1-4051-3539-9}}.</ref>

[[Oghul Qaimish]], the widow of [[Güyük Khan]], ruled as [[regent]] over the Mongol realm from 1249 to 1251.<ref>Xu, Shiduan (1998), "Oghul Qaimish, Empress of Mongol Emperor Dingzong," in Lily Xiao Hong Lee and Sue Wiles (eds), ''Biographical Dictionary of Chinese Women: Tang through Ming: 618–1644'', trans. Janine Burns, London & New York: Routledge, pp 299–300, {{ISBN|978-0-7656-4314-8}}.</ref> In 1250 the French diplomats André de Longjumeau, Guy de Longjumeau, and Jean de Carcassonne arrived at her court located along the [[Emil River]] (on the [[Emin Valley|Kazakh-Chinese border]]), bearing gifts and representing their sovereign [[Louis IX of France]], who desired a [[Seventh Crusade|military alliance]].<ref>Xu, Shiduan (1998), "Oghul Qaimish, Empress of Mongol Emperor Dingzong," in Lily Xiao Hong Lee and Sue Wiles (eds), ''Biographical Dictionary of Chinese Women: Tang through Ming: 618–1644'', trans. Janine Burns, London & New York: Routledge, pp 300–301, {{ISBN|978-0-7656-4314-8}}.</ref> Empress Qaimish viewed the gifts as [[Tributary state|tributary offerings]] and, in addition to gifts given in return, entrusted to Louis' diplomats, she sent the French monarch a letter demanding his submission as a [[vassal]].<ref>Xu, Shiduan (1998), "Oghul Qaimish, Empress of Mongol Emperor Dingzong", in Lily Xiao Hong Lee and Sue Wiles (eds), ''Biographical Dictionary of Chinese Women: Tang through Ming: 618–1644'', trans. Janine Burns, London & New York: Routledge, p. 301, {{ISBN|978-0-7656-4314-8}}.</ref>

The Franciscan missionary [[John of Montecorvino]] (Giovanni da Montecorvino<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=19 January 2010 |title=ASIA/CHINA - Franciscans in China: 1200–1977, 1,162 Friars Minor lived in China |url=http://www.fides.org/en/news/25844-ASIA_CHINA_Franciscans_in_China_1200_1977_1_162_Friars_Minor_lived_in_China |newspaper=Agenzia Fides |location= |access-date= }}</ref>) was ordered to China by [[Pope Nicholas III]] in 1279.<ref name="Herbermann1913">{{cite book|author=Charles George Herbermann|title=The Catholic Encyclopedia: An International Work of Reference on the Constitution, Doctrine, Discipline, and History of the Catholic Church|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CmwQAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA293&lpg=PA293&dq=China%27Franciscans+were+mentioned+in+his&source=bl&ots=dJh82eKGe5&sig=LPwnsuszoHTEu62WuH-JKnimNJs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6pcjZhfrOAhWJKh4KHbOtDE4Q6AEIVjAJ#v=onepage&q=China%27Franciscans%20were%20mentioned%20in%20his&f=false|year=1913|publisher=Universal Knowledge Foundation|pages=293–}}</ref><ref name="Clark2011">{{cite book|author=[[Anthony E. Clark]]|title=China's Saints: Catholic Martyrdom During the Qing (1644–1911)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rtJdwUjKhn8C&pg=PA114&lpg=PA114&dq=China%27Franciscans+were+mentioned+in+his&source=bl&ots=rn-gVPUrR4&sig=FYXaQsvxgMKVvrihFMogkS7d-G0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6pcjZhfrOAhWJKh4KHbOtDE4Q6AEIRzAF#v=onepage&q=China%27Franciscans%20were%20mentioned%20in%20his&f=false|date=7 April 2011|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-61146-017-9|pages=114–}}</ref> Montecorvino arrived in China at the end of 1293,<ref name="haw 2006 p172">Stephen G. Haw (2006), ''Marco Polo's China: a Venetian in the Realm of Kublai Khan'', London & New York: Routledge, p. 172, {{ISBN|0-415-34850-1}}.</ref> where he later translated the [[New Testament]] into the Mongol tongue, and converted 6,000 people (probably mostly Alans, Turks and Mongols rather than Chinese). He was joined by three bishops (Andre de Perouse, Gerard Albuini and Peregrino de Castello) and ordained [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Beijing|archbishop of Beijing]] by [[Pope Clement V]] in 1307.<ref name="fontana 2011 p116"/><ref name="haw 2006 p172"/> A community of [[Armenians in China]] sprang up during this period. They were converted to Catholicism by John of Montecorvino.<ref>Daniel H. Bays (9 June 2011). ''A New History of Christianity in China''. John Wiley & Sons. pp. 20–. {{ISBN|978-1-4443-4284-0}}.</ref><ref>Heup Young Kim (2011). ''Asian and Oceanic Christianities in Conversation: Exploring Theological Identities at Home and in Diaspora''. Rodopi. pp. 60–. {{ISBN|90-420-3299-5}}.</ref> Following the death of John of Montecorvino, [[Giovanni de Marignolli]] was dispatched to Beijing to become the new archbishop from 1342 to 1346 in an effort to maintain a Christian influence in the region.<ref name="haw 2006 p172"/><ref>Editors of the Encyclopædia Britannica. "[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Giovanni-dei-Marignolli#ref376989  Giovanni dei Marignolli: Italian Clergyman.]" ''Encyclopædia Britannica''. Accessed 6 September 2016.</ref><ref name="polo"/> Marignolli, although not mentioned by name in the ''[[History of Yuan]]'', is noted in that historical text as the "[[Frangistan|Frank]]" (''Fulang'') who provided the Yuan imperial court with an impressive [[war horse]] as a tributary gift.<ref name="haw 2006 p172"/>

On 15 March 1314 the killings of Francis de Petriolo, Monaldo of Ancona and Anthony of Milan occurred in China.<ref name="Robson2006">{{cite book|author=Michael Robson|title=The Franciscans in the Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KJOXBGHvB6MC&printsec=frontcover&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1s8bJ_PnOAhXImR4KHczyCtwQ6AEIVDAJ#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2006|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-1-84383-221-8|page=113}}</ref> This was followed by the Killing of James, Quanzhou's bishop, in 1362. His predecessors were Andrew, Peregrinus, and Gerard.<ref>Cordier, H. (1908). ''The Church in China. In The Catholic Encyclopedia''. New York: Robert Appleton Company. Retrieved September 6, 2016 from New Advent: http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/03669a.htm</ref>

The Franciscan Friar [[Odoric of Pordenone]] visited China.<ref name=polo>{{citation |first=Stephen G. |last=Haw |publisher=Psychology Press |year=2006|isbn=0-415-34850-1 |title=Marco Polo's China: a Venetian in the realm of Khubilai Khan |series=Volume 3 of Routledge studies in the early history of Asia |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CdE6Q_2yICIC&pg=PA52 |pages=52–57}}</ref> Friars in [[Hangzhou]] and [[Zhangzhou]] were visited by Odorico.<ref name="Robson2006 2">{{cite book|author=Michael Robson|title=The Franciscans in the Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KJOXBGHvB6MC&printsec=frontcover&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1s8bJ_PnOAhXImR4KHczyCtwQ6AEIVDAJ#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2006|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-1-84383-221-8|page=115}}</ref> His total travels took place from 1304 to 1340,<ref name="Herbermann1913 2">{{cite book|author=Charles George Herbermann|title=The Catholic Encyclopedia: An International Work of Reference on the Constitution, Doctrine, Discipline, and History of the Catholic Church|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2GcQAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjB_e2e__nOAhVLJR4KHbZvA3M4ChDoAQgiMAE#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=1913|publisher=Universal Knowledge Foundation|page=553}}</ref> although he first returned to Europe in 1330.<ref name="fontana 2011 p116"/> China's Franciscans were mentioned in his writings, the ''[[Odoric of Pordenone#Manuscripts and published editions|Itinerarium]]''.<ref name="Buell2003 2">{{cite book|author=Paul D. Buell|title=Historical Dictionary of the Mongol World Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aksYAAAAIAAJ&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjB_e2e__nOAhVLJR4KHbZvA3M4ChDoAQgdMAA|date=1 January 2003|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-4571-8|page=204}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/fra/FRAht04.html |title=6. History of the Franciscan Movement (4)  |last=Muscat  |first=Noel |date= |website=Christus Rex |publisher=FIOR-Malta |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>

In 1333, John de Montecorvino was officially replaced by Nicolaus de Bentra, who was chosen by [[Pope John XXII]].<ref name="halsall 2000"/><ref name="Mosheim1832">{{cite book|author=Johann Lorenz Mosheim|title=Institutes of Ecclesiastical History: Ancient and Modern&nbsp;... |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1wsQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA415&lpg=PA415&dq=nicolaus+de+bentra&source=bl&ots=c5rCVLN9HX&sig=GyTs3vlSn7-lYPvIBv3tDsn7DjM&hl=en&ei=ZX91TqyiHaTz0gHP0tntDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CDsQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=nicolaus%20de%20bentra&f=false|year=1832|publisher=A. H. Maltby|pages=415–}}</ref> There were complaints of the absence of the archbishop in 1338.<ref name="MosheimMosheim1999">{{cite book|author1=Johann Lorenz von Mosheim|author2=John Laurence Von Mosheim|title=Authentic Memoirs of the Christian Church in China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r92xuYbpbywC&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=nicolaus+de+bentra&source=bl&ots=IUreoOU2xj&sig=nNygBKAniDvWhYnCKCGvltxemg0&hl=en&ei=ZX91TqyiHaTz0gHP0tntDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=nicolaus%20de%20bentra&f=false|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Adegi Graphics LLC|isbn=978-1-4021-8109-2|pages=52–}}</ref><ref name="Mosheim1862">{{cite book|author=Johann Lorenz Mosheim|title=Authentic Memoirs of the Christian Church in China&nbsp;... |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bn5QAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=nicolaus+de+bentra&source=bl&ots=IUreoOU2xj&sig=nNygBKAniDvWhYnCKCGvltxemg0&hl=en&ei=ZX91TqyiHaTz0gHP0tntDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=nicolaus%20de%20bentra&f=false|year=1862|publisher=McGlashan & Gill|pages=52–}}</ref> [[Toghon Temür]] (the last Mongol ruler of the Yuan dynasty in China before their retreat to [[Mongolia]] to form the [[Northern Yuan dynasty]]) sent an embassy including Genoese Italians to [[Pope Benedict XII]] in 1336, requesting a new archbishop.<ref name="jackson 2005 p314"/> The pope answered by sending legates and ecclesiastical leaders to Khanbaliq in 1342, which included Giovanni de Marignolli.<ref name="fontana 2011 p116"/><ref name="jackson 2005 p314">Jackson, Peter (2005), ''The Mongols and the West: 1221–1410''. Harlow & New York: Longman, p. 314, {{ISBN|978-0-582-36896-5}}.</ref>

In 1370, following the ousting of the Mongols from China and the establishment of the Chinese [[Ming dynasty]], the Pope sent a new mission to China, comprising the Parisian theologian [[Guillaume du Pré]] as the new archbishop and 50 Franciscans. However, this mission disappeared, apparently eliminated by Emperor [[Zhu Yuanzhang]] of Ming.<ref>Roux (1993), p. 469.</ref> The Ming [[Hongwu Emperor]] sent a diplomatic letter to the [[Byzantine Empire]],<ref name="Grant2005">{{cite book|author=R. G. Grant|title=Battle: A Visual Journey Through 5,000 Years of Combat|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gb8qAQAAMAAJ&pg=PT102&dq=as+a+simple+peasant+of+Huai-yu,+conceived+the+patriotic+idea+to+save+the+people&hl=en&ei=F-XmTv6FHYHx0gHV4JTjCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEwQ6AEwBQ|year=2005|publisher=DK Pub.|isbn=978-0-7566-1360-0|pages=99–}}</ref> through a European in China named Nieh-ku-lun.<ref name="Hirth1885">{{cite book|author=Friedrich Hirth|title=China and the Roman Orient: Researches Into Their Ancient and Mediaeval Relations as Represented in Old Chinese Records|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dk4uAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA66&dq=as+a+simple+peasant+of+Huai-yu,+conceived+the+patriotic+idea+to+save+the+people&hl=en&ei=2c_mTtbnM-fn0QHK08D6CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=as%20a%20simple%20peasant%20of%20Huai-yu%2C%20conceived%20the%20patriotic%20idea%20to%20save%20the%20people&f=false|year=1885|publisher=G. Hirth|p =66}}</ref> [[John V Palaiologos]] was the Byzantine Emperor at the time the message was sent by Hongwu,<ref name="Luttwak2009">{{cite book|author=Edward Luttwak|title=The Grand Strategy of the Byzantine Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3cBjc6QCBXkC&pg=PA170&dq=as+a+simple+peasant+of+Huai-yu,+conceived+the+patriotic+idea+to+save+the+people&hl=en&ei=2c_mTtbnM-fn0QHK08D6CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=hongwu%20accession%20byzantium%20john%20v%20palaiologos&f=false|date=1 November 2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-03519-5|pages=169–}}</ref> with the proclamatory letter informing him about the establishment of the new Ming dynasty.<ref name="halsall 2000"/> The message was sent to the Byzantine ruler in September 1371 when Hongwu met with the merchant Nieh-ku-lun (捏古倫) from Fu lin (Byzantium).<ref name="Yule1915">{{cite book|author=Sir Henry Yule|title=Cathay and the Way Thither, Being a Collection of Medieval Notices of China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rMIWlq6JeccC&pg=PA12&dq=as+a+simple+peasant+of+Huai-yu,+conceived+the+patriotic+idea+to+save+the+people&hl=en&ei=2c_mTtbnM-fn0QHK08D6CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=as%20a%20simple%20peasant%20of%20Huai-yu%2C%20conceived%20the%20patriotic%20idea%20to%20save%20the%20people&f=false|<!-- url2=http://www.archive.org/stream/cathaywaythither03yule#page/12/mode/2up/search/our+middle|-->year=1915|publisher=Asian Educational Services|isbn=978-81-206-1966-1|pages=12–}}</ref><ref name="Cordier1967">{{cite book|author=Henri Cordier|title=Cathay and the Way Thither: Being a Collection of Medieval Notices of China|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=2c_mTtbnM-fn0QHK08D6CQ&ct=result&id=u1nPZVNfsRoC&dq=as+a+simple+peasant+of+Huai-yu%2C+conceived+the+patriotic+idea+to+save+the+people&q=Huai-yu|year=1967|publisher=Kraus Reprint|page=12}}</ref> The [[Khanbaliq]] bishop Nicolaus de Bentra is speculated to be the same person as Nieh-ku-lun, for instance, by [[Emil Bretschneider]] in 1888.<ref name="Yule1915 2">{{cite book|author=Sir Henry Yule|title=Cathay and the Way Thither, Being a Collection of Medieval Notices of China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rMIWlq6JeccC&pg=PA13&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrraCw9fnOAhXBGR4KHaWMDgAQ6AEIIDAA#v=onepage&q=nicholas%20in%20the%20year%201338%20had%20not%20yet%20arrive%20in%20peking%20for%20the%20christians%20there%20compalined%20ina%20letter%20written%20at%20the%20above%20that%20that%20they%20were%20eight%20years%20without%20a%20curate&f=false|year=1915|publisher=Asian Educational Services|isbn=978-81-206-1966-1|pages=13–}}</ref><ref name="Bretschneider1871">{{cite book|author=E. Bretschneider|title=On the Knowledge Possessed by the Ancient Chinese of the Arabs and Arabian Colonies: And Other Western Countries, Mentioned in Chinese Books|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kZPMZ0AkLzoC&pg=PA25&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrraCw9fnOAhXBGR4KHaWMDgAQ6AEIJTAB#v=onepage&q=nicholas%20in%20the%20year%201338%20had%20not%20yet%20arrive%20in%20peking%20for%20the%20christians%20there%20compalined%20ina%20letter%20written%20at%20the%20above%20that%20that%20they%20were%20eight%20years%20without%20a%20curate&f=false|year=1871|publisher=Trübner & Company|pages=25–}}</ref> More recently, Edward N. Luttwak (2009) also mused that Nicolaus de Bentra and this alleged Byzantine merchant Nieh-ku-lin were one and the same.<ref name="Luttwak2009 2">{{cite book|author=Edward Luttwak|title=The Grand Strategy of the Byzantine Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3cBjc6QCBXkC&pg=PA170&dq=as+a+simple+peasant+of+Huai-yu,+conceived+the+patriotic+idea+to+save+the+people&hl=en&ei=2c_mTtbnM-fn0QHK08D6CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=as%20a%20simple%20peasant%20of%20Huai-yu%2C%20conceived%20the%20patriotic%20idea%20to%20save%20the%20people&f=false|date=1 November 2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-03519-5|pages=169–170}}</ref>

Friar William of Parto, Cosmas, and John de' Marignolli were among the Catholic clerics in China.<ref name="Society1967">{{cite book|author=Hakluyt Society|title=Works|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n33gAAAAMAAJ&q=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrraCw9fnOAhXBGR4KHaWMDgAQ6AEIKzAC|year=1967|publisher=Kraus Reprint|page=13}}</ref> The ''Oriens Christianus'' by [[Michel Le Quien]] (1661–1733) recorded the names of Khanbaliq's previous bishops and archbishops.<ref name="Cordier1967 2">{{cite book|author=Henri Cordier|title=Cathay and the Way Thither: Being a Collection of Medieval Notices of China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u1nPZVNfsRoC&q=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrraCw9fnOAhXBGR4KHaWMDgAQ6AEIMDAD|year=1967|publisher=Kraus Reprint|page=13}}</ref><ref name="Yule1998">{{cite book|author=Sir Henry Yule|title=Cathay and the Way Thither: Missionary friars. Rashíduddín - Pegolotti - Marignolli|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dNYMAQAAMAAJ&q=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&dq=nicholas+in+the+year+1338+had+not+yet+arrive+in+peking+for+the+christians+there+compalined+ina+letter+written+at+the+above+that+that+they+were+eight+years+without+a+curate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrraCw9fnOAhXBGR4KHaWMDgAQ6AEINTAE|year=1998|publisher=Munshiram Manoharlal Publishers Pvt. Limited|isbn=978-81-215-0841-4|page=13}}</ref>

==Captives==
For his travels from 1253 to 1255, the Franciscan monk [[William of Rubruck]] reported numerous Europeans in Central Asia. He described German prisoners who had been enslaved and forced to mine gold and manufacture iron weapons in the Mongol town of Bolat, near [[Talas, Kyrgyzstan]].<ref>Jack Goody (2012), ''Metals, Culture, and Capitalism: an Essay on the Origins of the Modern World'', Cambridge & New York: Cambridge University Press, p. 226, {{ISBN|978-1-107-02962-0}}.</ref><ref name="Spence1999">{{cite book|author=Jonathan D. Spence|title=The Chan's Great Continent: China in Western Minds|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AVk1zq_C7_kC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Yan+Zhitui+Family+instructions+for+the+Yan+clan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiEipWD2_fOAhXEuB4KHdo7Ask4RhDoAQhWMAg#v=onepage&q=Yan%20Zhitui%20Family%20instructions%20for%20the%20Yan%20clan&f=false|year=1999|publisher=W. W. Norton|isbn=978-0-393-31989-7|pages=1–2}}</ref> In [[Karakorum]], the Mongol capital, he met a [[Paris]]ian named Guillaume de Buchier, and Pâquette, a woman from the French city of [[Metz]], who had both been captured in [[Hungary]] during the [[Mongol invasions of Europe]]. He also mentions [[Hungarians]] and [[Russians]], and it is also known that 30,000 [[Alans]], a group of [[Sarmatian]] tribes, formed the [[Asud]] guard of the Mongol court in [[Beijing]].<ref name="Roux, p.465"/>

==Spread of Chinese gunpowder==
<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:Heilongjianghandcannon.jpg|thumb|The [[Heilongjiang hand cannon]], dated to 1288, is a [[Yuan dynasty]] hand cannon, and currently the world's oldest surviving firearm. This image is a digitalization of the hand cannon photograph published in 1973, from: "A Bronze Bombard Excavated at Banlachengzi in [[Acheng District]] in [[Heilongjiang Province]]," by Wei Guozhong.]] -->
{{main article|History of gunpowder}}
{{further information|History of the firearm|History of artillery}}
[[William of Rubruck]], a Flemish missionary who visited the Mongol court of [[Mongke Khan]] at [[Karakorum]] and returned to Europe in 1257, was a friend of the English philosopher and scientific thinker [[Roger Bacon]]. The latter recorded the earliest known European recipe for [[gunpowder]] in his ''[[Opus Majus]]'' of 1267.<ref>Needham, Joseph; et al. (1987), ''Science and Civilisation in China, Vol. V, Pt. 7'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp 48–50, {{ISBN|978-0-521-30358-3}}.</ref><ref>Pacey, Arnold (1991), ''Technology in World Civilization: A Thousand-year History'', Boston: MIT Press, p. 45, {{ISBN|0-262-66072-5}}.</ref> This came more than two centuries after the [[Wujing Zongyao|first known Chinese description]] of the formula for gunpowder in 1044, during the [[Song dynasty]].<ref>Ebrey, Patricia Buckley (2010) [1996]. ''The Cambridge Illustrated History of China'' (2nd ed.). New York: Cambridge University Press, p. 138, {{ISBN|978-0-521-12433-1}}.</ref><ref>Needham, Joseph (1987). ''Science and Civilisation in China: Military technology: The Gunpowder Epic, Volume 5, Part 7''. New York: Cambridge University Press, pp 118–124. {{ISBN|978-0-521-30358-3}}.</ref> The earliest use of Chinese [[fire lance|prototype firearms]] occurred at an 1132 siege during the [[Jin-Song Wars]],<ref>Needham, Joseph (1986), ''Science & Civilisation in China, V:7: The Gunpowder Epic'', Cambridge University Press, p. 222, {{ISBN|0-521-30358-3}}.</ref><ref>Chase, Kenneth Warren (2003). ''Firearms: A Global History to 1700''. Cambridge University Press, p. 31, {{ISBN|978-0-521-82274-9}}.</ref><ref>Peter Allan Lorge (2008), ''The Asian Military Revolution: from Gunpowder to the Bomb'', Cambridge University Press, pp 33–34, {{ISBN|978-0-521-60954-8}}.</ref> whereas [[Heilongjiang hand cannon|the oldest surviving]] bronze [[hand cannon]] dates to 1288 during the Yuan period.<ref>Chase, Kenneth Warren (2003). Firearms: A Global History to 1700. Cambridge University Press, p. 32, {{ISBN|978-0-521-82274-9}}.</ref><ref>Needham, Joseph (1986), ''Science & Civilisation in China, V:7: The Gunpowder Epic'', Cambridge University Press, p. 293, {{ISBN|0-521-30358-3}}.</ref> Following the [[Mongol invasions of Japan]] (1274–1281), [[:File:Mōko Shūrai Ekotoba.jpg|a Japanese scroll painting]] depicted [[Thunder crash bomb|explosive bombs]] used by Yuan-dynasty forces against their [[samurai]].<ref>Stephen Turnbull (19 February 2013). ''[url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qo4amAg_ygIC&pg=PT41 The Mongol Invasions of Japan 1274 and 1281]''. Osprey Publishing. pp 41–42. {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0045-9}}. Retrieved 6 September 2016.</ref> By 1326 the earliest artistic depiction of a [[gun]] was made in Europe by [[Walter de Milemete]].<ref>Kelly, Jack (2004), ''Gunpowder: Alchemy, Bombards, & Pyrotechnics: The History of the Explosive that Changed the World'', Basic Books, p. 29, {{ISBN|0-465-03718-6}}.</ref> [[Petrarch]] wrote in 1350 that [[cannon]]s were then a common sight on the European battlefield.<ref>Norris, John (2003), ''Early Gunpowder Artillery: 1300–1600'', Marlborough: The Crowood Press, p. 19.</ref>

==Diplomatic missions to Europe==
[[Image:ArghunLetterToPhilippeLeBelExtract1289.jpg|thumb|Extract of the letter of [[Arghun]] to [[Philip IV of France|Philip IV]], in the [[Uyghur-Mongolian script]], dated 1289, in which [[Rabban Bar Sauma]] is mentioned. The seal is that of the Great Khan, with Chinese Script: "辅国安民之宝", which means "Seal of the upholder of the State and the purveyor of peace to the People". [[French National Archives]].]]
{{main article|Franco-Mongol alliance|Byzantine-Mongol alliance|Chinese exploration}}
[[Rabban Bar Sauma]], a Nestorian Christian [[Kingdom of Qocho|Uyghur Turk]] born in [[Zhongdu]] (later Khanbaliq, Beijing, capital of the [[Jurchen people|Jurchen]]-led [[Jin dynasty (1115-1234)|Jin dynasty]]), China,<ref name="encyclopedia britannica raban bar sauma"/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZRFAAAAMAAJ&dq=One+such+Uigur+Christian%2C+Rabban+Marcos%2C+born+near+Peking%2C+was+appointed+in+1281+patriarch-general+of+the+Nestorian+Church+with+Baghdad+as+his+place+of+residence+.+His+close+friend%2C+Rabban+Sauma%2C+another+Christian+of+Uigur+race+from&q=christian+rabban+marcos+1281+patriarch+general+church|title=The invention of printing in China and its spread westward|author=Thomas Francis Carter|editor=|year=1955|publisher=Ronald Press Co.|edition=2|location=|page=171|isbn=|pages=|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref><ref>Moule, A. C., ''Christians in China before 1500'', 94 & 103; also Pelliot, Paul in ''T'oung-pao'' 15(1914), pp. 630–36.</ref> was sent to Europe in 1287 as an ambassador for [[Arghun]], ruler of the [[Ilkhanate]] and grandnephew of [[Kublai Khan]].<ref name="jackson 2005 p169">Peter Jackson (2005), ''The Mongols and the West, 1221–1410'', Pearson Education, p. 169, {{ISBN|0-582-36896-0}}.</ref> He was preceded by [[Isa Kelemechi]], an [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] Nestorian Christian who worked as a [[Chinese astronomy|court astronomer]] for Kublai Khan in Khanbaliq,<ref>[[Foltz, Richard]] (2010), ''Religions of the Silk Road'', Palgrave Macmillan, 2nd edition, pp. 125–126, {{ISBN|978-0-230-62125-1}}.</ref><ref>Thomas F. Glick; Steven John Livesey; Faith Wallis (2005), ''Medieval science, technology, and medicine: an encyclopedia'' London & New York: Routledge, p. 485, {{ISBN|0-415-96930-1}}.</ref> and was sent by Arghun to [[Pope Honorius IV]] in 1285.<ref name="jackson 2005 p169"/><ref>William Bayne Fisher; John Andrew Boyle (1968). ''The Cambridge history of Iran'', London & New York: Cambridge University Press, p.370, {{ISBN|0-521-06936-X}}.</ref> A decade earlier, Bar Sauma had originally set out [[Christian pilgrimage|on a pilgrimage]] to [[Jerusalem]], passing through [[Gansu]] and [[Khotan]] in [[Northwest China]], yet spent time in [[Armenia]] and [[Baghdad]] instead to avoid getting caught up in nearby armed conflicts.<ref name="encyclopedia britannica raban bar sauma"/> He had been accompanied by [[Yahballaha III|Rabban Markos]], [[History of the Uyghur people|another Uyghur]] Nestorian Christian from China who was elected as the [[List of Patriarchs of the Church of the East|Patriarch of the Eastern Church]] and advised Arghun Khan to have Bar Sauma lead the diplomatic mission to Europe.<ref name="encyclopedia britannica raban bar sauma">Kathleen Kuiper & editors of Encyclopædia Britannica (Aug 31, 2006). "[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Rabban-bar-Sauma Rabban bar Sauma: Mongol Envoy]." ''Encyclopædia Britannica'' (online source). Accessed 6 September 2016.</ref><ref>Morris Rossabi (2014). ''From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi''. Leiden & Boston: Brill, pp 385–386, {{ISBN|978-90-04-28529-3}}.</ref>

Bar Sauma, who spoke [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Persian language|Persian]], and [[Old Uyghur language|Old Uyghur]], traveled with a cohort of Italians who served as translators, with Europeans communicating to him in Persian.<ref>Morris Rossabi (2014). ''From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi''. BRILL, pp. 385–387, {{ISBN|978-90-04-28529-3}}.</ref> Bar Sauma is the first known person from China to reach Europe, where he convened with the Byzantine Emperor [[Andronikos II Palaiologos]], [[Philip IV of France]], [[Edward I of England]], and [[Pope Nicholas IV]] (shortly after the death of Pope Honorius IV) to form an alliance against the [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk Sultanate]].<ref name="encyclopedia britannica raban bar sauma"/><ref>Morris Rossabi (2014). ''From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi''. Leiden & Boston: Brill, pp. 386–421, {{ISBN|978-90-04-28529-3}}.</ref><ref>William Bayne Fisher; John Andrew Boyle (1968). ''The Cambridge history of Iran'', London & New York: Cambridge University Press, pp 370–371, {{ISBN|0-521-06936-X}}.</ref> Edward N. Luttwak depicts the arrival of these Nestorian envoys to the court of the Byzantine ruler Andronikos II as something akin to "receiving mail from his in-law in Beijing," since Kublai Khan was a grandson of [[Genghis Khan]] and Andronikos had two half-sisters who were married to great-grandsons of Genghis.<ref name="luttwak 2009 p169">Luttwak, Edward N. (2009). ''The Grand Strategy of the Byzantine Empire''. Cambridge and London: The Belknap Press of Harvard University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-674-03519-5}}, p. 169.</ref> Moving further west, Bar Sauma witnessed a naval battle at the [[Bay of Naples]], Italy in June, 1287 between the [[Capetian House of Anjou|Angevins]] and the [[Kingdom of Aragon]], while being hosted by [[Charles Martel of Anjou]], whose father [[Charles II of Naples]] was imprisoned in Aragon (in modern Spain) at the time.<ref>Morris Rossabi (2014). ''From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi''. Leiden & Boston: Brill, p. 399, {{ISBN|978-90-04-28529-3}}.</ref> Aside from his desire to see Christian sites, churches, and relics, Bar Sauma also showed a keen interest in the [[Medieval university|university life]] and curricula of [[Paris]], which Morris Rossabi contends was rooted in how exotic it must have seemed [[Ancient higher-learning institutions|from his perspective]] and [[Madrasa|educational background in Muslim Persia]] and [[Academies (Shuyuan)|Chinese]] [[Confucianism|Confucian teaching]].<ref>Morris Rossabi (2014). ''From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi''. Leiden & Boston: Brill, p. 416–417, {{ISBN|978-90-04-28529-3}}.</ref> Although he managed to secure an audience with these leaders of [[Christendom]] and exchanged letters from them to Arghun Khan, none of these Christian monarchs were fully committed to an alliance with the latter.<ref name="encyclopedia britannica raban bar sauma"/>

==Renewed contacts during the Ming dynasty==
[[Image:Ricci Guangqi 2.jpg|thumb|The [[Italy|Italian]] [[Jesuit]] [[Matteo Ricci]] (left) and the [[Chinese mathematics|Chinese mathematician]] [[Xu Guangqi]] (right) published the [[Chinese language|Chinese]] edition of ''[[Euclid's Elements]]'' (幾何原本) in 1607.]]
{{further information|Sino-Portuguese relations|Jesuit China missions|History of the Ming dynasty|Chinese Rites controversy}}
In 1368 the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty collapsed amid widespread internal revolt during the [[Red Turban Rebellion]], whose [[Han Chinese]] leader would become [[Hongwu Emperor|the founding emperor]] of the [[Ming dynasty]].<ref>Ebrey, Patricia Buckley (1999), ''The Cambridge Illustrated History of China'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp 190–191, {{ISBN|0-521-66991-X}}.</ref> A formal resumption of direct trade and contact with Europeans would not be seen until the 16th century, [[Portuguese discoveries|initiated by the Portuguese]] during the [[Age of Discovery]].<ref name="fontana 2011 p117">Fontana, Michela (2011), ''Matteo Ricci: a Jesuit in the Ming Court'', Lanham: Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, p. 117, {{ISBN|978-1-4422-0586-4}}.</ref> The first Portuguese explorer to land in southern China was [[Jorge Álvares]], who in May 1513 arrived at [[Lintin Island]] in the [[Pearl River Delta]] to engage in trade.<ref>John E. Wills, Jr., (1998), "Relations with Maritime Europeans, 1514–1662," in Mote, Frederick W. and Denis Twitchett (eds.), ''The Cambridge History of China: Volume 8, The Ming Dynasty, 1368–1644, Part 2'', 333–375, New York: Cambridge University Press, p. 336, {{ISBN|0-521-24333-5}} (Hardback edition).</ref> This was followed by [[Rafael Perestrello]], a cousin of the wife of [[Christopher Columbus]], who landed at [[Guangzhou]] in 1516 after a voyage from newly conquered [[Portuguese Malacca]].<ref>Brook, Timothy (1998), ''The Confusions of Pleasure: Commerce and Culture in Ming China'', Berkeley: University of California Press, p. 124, {{ISBN|0-520-22154-0}} (Paperback).</ref> Although the 1517 mission by [[Fernão Pires de Andrade]] ended in disaster and his imprisonment by Ming authorities, relations would be smoothed over by Leonel de Sousa, the [[Governor of Macau|first governor]] of the [[History of Macau|Portuguese trade colony]] at [[Macau]], China, in the [[Luso-Chinese agreement (1554)|Luso-Chinese treaty of 1554]].<ref>John E. Wills, Jr., (1998), "Relations with Maritime Europeans, 1514–1662," in Mote, Frederick W. and Denis Twitchett (eds.), ''The Cambridge History of China: Volume 8, The Ming Dynasty, 1368–1644, Part 2'', 333–375, New York: Cambridge University Press, p. 338–344, {{ISBN|0-521-24333-5}} (Hardback edition).</ref> The writings of [[Gaspar da Cruz]], [[Juan Gonzáles de Mendoza]], and [[Antonio de Morga]] all impacted the Western view and understanding of China at the time, offering intricate details about its society and items of trade.<ref>Robinson, David M. "Banditry and the Subversion of State Authority in China: The Capital Region during the Middle Ming Period (1450–1525)," in ''Journal of Social History'' (Spring 2000): 527–563.</ref><ref>Brook, Timothy. (1998). ''The Confusions of Pleasure: Commerce and Culture in Ming China''. Berkeley: University of California Press. {{ISBN|0-520-22154-0}}, p. 206.</ref>

The Italian Jesuit missionary [[Matteo Ricci]] would be the first European invited into the Ming-era [[Forbidden City]] in [[Beijing]] (during the reign of the [[Wanli Emperor]]), where in 1602 he would publish his [[Kunyu Wanguo Quantu|map of the world]] in [[Chinese characters|Chinese]] that introduced the existence of the [[Americas|American continents]] to [[Chinese geography|Chinese geographers]].<ref name="Abbe">{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/art/79576487.html|title=Million-dollar map coming to Minnesota|last=Abbe|first=Mary|date=2009-12-18|work= Star Tribune|publisher=Star Tribune Company|accessdate=6 September 2016|location=Minneapolis}}</ref> He arrived in Macau in 1582, when he began to learn the Chinese language and information about China's ancient culture, yet was unaware of the events that had transpired there since the end of the Franciscan missions in the mid 14th century and establishment of the Ming dynasty.<ref>Fontana, Michela (2011), ''Matteo Ricci: a Jesuit in the Ming Court'', Lanham: Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, pp 18–35, 116–118, {{ISBN|978-1-4422-0586-4}}.</ref> Since that time [[Islamicisation and Turkicisation of Xinjiang|the Islamic world]] presented an obstacle for the West in reaching East Asia and, barring the grand [[treasure voyages]] of the 15th-century admiral [[Zheng He]], the Ming dynasty had largely pursued [[Haijin|policies of isolationism]] that kept it from seeking far-flung diplomatic contacts.<ref name="fontana 2011 p117"/><ref>The Ming Empire was at least willing to engage in conflicts nearby, however, when it offered relief forces to its tributary state [[Joseon]] (Korea) against [[Toyotomi Hideyoshi|invading Japanese forces]] in the [[Imjin War]] (1592–1598). See Patricia Ebrey, Anne Walthall, James Palais, (2006), ''East Asia: A Cultural, Social, and Political History'', Boston: Houghton Mifflin Company, p. 214, {{ISBN|0-618-13384-4}}.</ref>

