[[File:Flagge Großherzogtum Baden (1871-1891).svg|thumb|3:5 {{FIAV|historical}} Flag of Baden (1871-1891)]]
[[File:Flagge Großherzogtum Baden (1891-1918).svg|thumb|3:5 {{FIAV|historical}} Flag of Baden (1891-1935, 1947-1952)]]
The '''flag of Baden''' displayed a combination of [[yellow]] and [[red]], the heraldic colours of the former [[Germany|German]] state of [[Baden]]. 

==Overview==
A red-yellow [[Commons:Bicolor flags|bicolour]] was introduced as the flag of the [[Grand Duchy of Baden]] (1806–1918) in 1871. This was replaced with a yellow-red-yellow [[triband (flag)|triband]] in 1891. Following the abolition of the monarchy at the end of [[World War I]], the [[Republic of Baden]] was established, which continued to use this triband flag. After the [[Nazi Party]] came to power in Germany in 1933, the individual German states and their symbols were eventually suppressed. After [[World War II]], the southern half of Baden became part of the [[Allied Occupation Zones in Germany#French Zone of Occupation|French Occupation Zone]] and established as [[South Baden]]. South Baden used the yellow-red-yellow triband as its flag until the state's disestablishment in 1952, when it became part of<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Baden-Württemberg|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1E1-BadenWur.html|encyclopedia=[[The Columbia Encyclopedia]]}}</ref> the modern [[States of Germany|German state]] of [[Baden-Württemberg]].

The flag is still a common sight in the Baden region today, as it is used by many private citizens.
[[File:Burg Rötteln Blick vom Bergfried.jpg|thumb|left|The Baden flag flown from [[Burg Rötteln|Rötteln castle]] in [[Lörrach]]]]

